Poland and the cosmos.
In the meeting of ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency celebrated the past week it was accepted to Poland like twelfth member of THAT. It is the second Member State of THAT of the old block of East Europe, after the Czech Republic, that became total member the 12 of November of 2008).
Poland initiated an intense collaboration with THAT in 1994 and during the later years it participated in the commission of projects of the agency.
Nevertheless, the way of Poland towards the cosmos began long before.
The enthusiastic Poles already dedicated themselves to the flights to the space before World War II, although not always its work was understood.
Memory, for example, the conference of A. Šternfeld in the astronomical observatory of Warsaw in which, the 6 of December of 1933, “Introduction to the cosmonautics” presented its ideas on the pioneering study.
The ideas of the young engineer (been born the 1905) left the indifferent assistants and, years later, Šternfeld it remembered that the Dr. Jan Gadomski had been the unique one that had shown interest in their work.
In 1934 Šternfeld obtained in France the prize Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch by its “Introduction to the cosmonautics”.
Doctor Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966), mentioned previously, later became a great impeller of astronomy and the cosmonautics.
It published hundreds of articles in Polish magazines and wrote a series of books dedicated to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski became a promoter of the cosmonautics, was well-known anywhere in the world and its contribution to science was compensated when its name to one of craters of the dark side of the moon was put.
In year 1925 a dresina was already constructed in Poland that was going to be provided of a motor of rockets.
