As of year 1933 the Polish artillery began to dedicate itself to the missiles.
The investigation was funded by the Komórka Techniki Uzbrojenia in collaboration with Prof. Mieczyslawem Wolfkem and Prof. Gustawem Mokrzyckiegim.
From the conserved material, one becomes evident that the investigation arrived at the stage of the troop trialses.
However, with the arrival of the German troops, the investigation was interrupted.
In 1937 it appeared in the specialized press the prototype of a photoelectric missile of hunting designed by Rohoziński engineer and the following year torpeda was published the study “Rakieta - powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza”, of Leliwa-Krzywoblocki author.
Both projects were destined to the military use of the motors for missiles.
Shortly before the war, the provisional scientific advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was in charge of all the projects of techniques of missiles use to militate and coordinated all the works.
The committee was founded on 1937, but after two years of activity, it was interrupted by the beginning of the war.
Other studies dedicated to the cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Society of Astronautics (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
In the edition of November of 1954 of the Problemy magazine reference to the society with four very extensive articles dedicated to the astronautics is made for the first time.
In one of them, of Prof. M. Subotowicze, the creation of a society seted out that would dedicate itself to the cosmonautics.
At that time already projects of artificial satellites had started up and was obvious that the cosmic investigation was a discipline with perspective de futuro.
Since the beginning of 1956 the Polish Society of Astronáutica (PTA) aspired to comprise of the Federation the International of Astronautics (founded on 1951) and autumn of that same year the Pta became total member.
The year following the first president of the Pta, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), passed to be vice-president of the Federation Internacional of Astronautics.
It carried out this position until his death in 1959.
As of the 1956, the Pta significantly participated in the development of the sounding rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), that was a success and it became the first Polish rocket in which scientific research took to end.
First type RM-1 was finalized in 1957 and the 10 of October of 1958 were sent for the first time.
The rocket had an apogee of 1,800 meters, about 80 cm in length and it did not arrive at the 5 kg of weight.
Later, it was finished constructing version RM-1A and in summer of 1959 the aerial tests of rockets RM-2 of two stages in the desert of Błędów began.
The rocket measured 1.4 meters and weighed about 11.5 kg.
Another type of developing rocket was going to be object of real scientific study. Rocket RM-34 was going to have an apogee of 14.5 km and its mission would be to control the height wind.
Nevertheless, in 1962 the works were suspended.
The successor of the first rockets of type RM was the Meteor-1 rocket, that was constructed during years 1962 and 1965.
It was designed like two-stage rocket, with a length overall of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (Meteor-1A calls, -1B and -1C), who were different themselves to each other by the space available for scientific equipment.
In the Meteor-1A rocket the space available for the volume was of 0.4 liters, in the Meteor-1B of 0.34 liters and the Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters.
